04863nam a22006375i 9780822388371DE-B159720201125033335.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201125t20062006ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223883717 a10.1515/97808223883712doi  a(DE-B1597)554027  a(OCoLC)1224278731  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aPQ307.H6bL83 2006 7aLIT0041502bisacsh1 aLucey, Michael, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aNever Say I :bSexuality and the First Person in Colette, Gide, and Proust /cMichael Lucey; Michèle Aina Barale, Eve Kosofsky Sedgwick, Michael Moon, Jonathan Goldberg. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2006] 4c©2006  a1 online resource (330 p.) :b4 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSeries Q00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Referring to Same-Sex Sexualities in the First Person -- t1. Gide, Bourget, and Proust Talking -- t2. Questions of Register in and around 1902 -- t3. Colette, the Moulin Rouge, and Les Vrilles -- t4. Gide and Posterity -- t5. Proust's Queer Metalepses -- t6. Sodom and Gomorrah: Proust's Narrator's First Person -- tEpilogue -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aNever Say I reveals the centrality of representations of sexuality, and particularly same-sex sexual relations, to the evolution of literary prose forms in twentieth-century France. Rethinking the social and literary innovation of works by Marcel Proust, André Gide, and Colette, Michael Lucey considers these writers' production of a first-person voice in which matters related to same-sex sexuality could be spoken of. He shows how their writings and careers took on political and social import in part through the contribution they made to the representation of social groups that were only slowly coming to be publicly recognized. Proust, Gide, and Colette helped create persons and characters, points of view, and narrative practices from which to speak and write about, for, or as people attracted to those of the same sex.Considering novels along with journalism, theatrical performances, correspondences, and face-to-face encounters, Lucey focuses on the interlocking social and formal dimensions of using the first person. He argues for understanding the first person not just as a grammatical category but also as a collectively produced social artifact, demonstrating that Proust's, Gide's, and Colette's use of the first person involved a social process of assuming the authority to speak about certain issues, or on behalf of certain people. Lucey reveals these three writers as both practitioners and theorists of the first person; he traces how, when they figured themselves or other first persons in certain statements regarding same-sex identity, they self-consciously called attention to the creative effort involved in doing so.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Nov 2020) 0aAutobiography in literature. 0aFrench literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aHomosexuality and literaturezFrance. 0aHomosexuality in literature. 0aLesbianism in literature. 0aSelf in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / French.2bisacsh1 aBarale, Michèle Aina, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGoldberg, Jonathan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMoon, Michael, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSedgwick, Eve Kosofsky, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822388371zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyt